{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":31153,"record_hash":"sha256:92708cb2d1df89d076046c6a065e377a62e94702a2b8ed6f10736111c76b828c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:27:19.013Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 89a26a\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1927\nOutput:\n# Agentlog Sync Lifecycle\n\nThis note sketches a future hidden command:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sync [--remote <name>]\n```\n\nThe command should exchange only GitButler agentlog metadata. Capture remains a\nlocal operation; sync is the explicit lifecycle step that sends captured\nmetadata to a remote and receives metadata captured elsewhere.\n\n## Goals\n\n- Send and receive agentlog metadata through GitMeta refs.\n- Keep the command scoped to agentlog keys, not every shareable GitMeta key.\n- Materialize received metadata back into local SQLite so readers can query it\n  normally.\n- Reuse GitMeta library APIs for serialization, fetch, push, conflict handling,\n  and materialization.\n- Keep hook/capture commands local-only and fast.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Do not make capture or hooks push metadata.\n- Do not sync unrelated GitMeta namespaces.\n- Do not infer branch or pull request ownership.\n- Do not implement custom Git transport in `but-agentlog`.\n- Do not silently install persistent project filter rules just to make this\n  command work.\n\n## Agentlog Key Scope\n\nAgentlog sync should include:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-sessions\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n```\n\nThe first key may appear on the `project` target as the session index and on\nfuture branch/change/commit targets as relationship references. Include both.\nThe durable session data stays on the `project` target.\n\nKeep the matcher exact:\n\n```text\nkey == \"gitbutler:agent-sessions\"\nkey starts with \"gitbutler:agent-session:\"\n```\n\nDo not match broader prefixes such as `gitbutler:agent`, because future\nGitButler metadata under nearby names may have different privacy or lifecycle\nrules.\n\nNo `meta:local:*` values should be synced. If future implementation adds\nprivate or machine-local agentlog state, keep it outside this command's\npublished key scope.\n\n## Command Shape\n\nInitial POC command:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sync [--remote <name>]\n```\n\nWhen `--remote` is omitted, u\n[TRUNCATED]\nlize/materialize bookkeeping\n- normal Git fetch/push transport\n- bounded non-fast-forward retry\n\nPrefer APIs that make this concrete use case easy to write correctly, then leave\nadditional routing, multiple scopes per command, custom merge policy, and extra\nreporting for later.\n\nKeep the implementation pragmatic and small. Less code is easier to understand,\ntest, and change while the feature is still early. Do not code-golf or obscure\nthe flow, but prefer direct functions, simple data structures, and focused tests\nover speculative extensibility.\n\nUse [Agentlog Maintainability Playbook](maintainability-playbook.md) at useful\ncheckpoints, especially after the GitMeta scoped-sync API takes shape and after\n`but agentlog sync` is wired. Treat it as a way to find simplification and\nboundary issues, not as a mandatory ceremony after every small edit.\n\n## Suggested Ref Shape\n\nAgentlog sync is key-scoped first. The serialized local ref and remote ref\nshould mirror that scope as directly as GitMeta allows:\n\n```text\nlocal:  refs/meta/local/agentlog\nremote: refs/meta/agentlog\n```\n\nThis is cleaner than publishing agentlog into the default metadata ref because:\n\n- the command can honestly claim to sync only agentlog data\n- future GitButler metadata can have different privacy and publishing policy\n- large transcript data can be reasoned about separately from smaller metadata\n- a backend or teammate can fetch/materialize only the agentlog key scope\n\nThe ref suffix should match what GitMeta stores locally for this key scope.\nAvoid a design where local storage says `agentlog` but the remote ref uses\nunrelated product vocabulary.\n\n## Ordering And Dedupe\n\nRemote materialization can merge metadata from multiple machines. Readers should\nnot depend on stored GitMeta list order. After sync, consumers should:\n\n- dedupe transcript records by `record_hash`\n- sort by `source_key` and `record_index` within one source\n- use `timestamp`, `source_key`, `record_index`, and `record_hash` as stable\n  ordering inputs across multiple sources\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:27:19.013Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}